  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 16:10",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Chronicles 16:10",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Asa was wroth with the seer — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Though the reproof came from God by one that was known to be his messenger; though it was just, and the reasoning fair, and all intended for his good, yet he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "was wroth ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "with the prophet; nay, he was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in a rage with him, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for telling him of his folly. Is this Asa? Is this he whose heart is said to have been perfect with the Lord? How needful that advice, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Let him that standeth take heed lest he fall! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A wise man! and yet ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in a rage! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "An Israelite! and yet in a rage with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a prophet!",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A good man! and yet impatient of reproof, and cannot bear to be told of his faults! Lord, what is man when left to himself! They that idolize their own conduct, cannot bear contradiction; and they that indulge a peevish, passionate temper, may be transported by it into impieties as well as indecencies, and will some time or other, probably, fly in the face of God himself. See what gall and wormwood this root of bitterness bore! Asa ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "put him in the prison-house — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Him whom he knew to be a prophet of the Lord, and God’s messenger to him! Or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in the house of the stocks, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(as some read it,) in which the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "feet, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or, as some of the Hebrews say, the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "necks ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "of the prisoners were locked up. God’s prophets meet with many that cannot bear reproof; still, however, they must proceed on doing their duty. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And Asa oppressed some of the people the same time ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Probably such as owned the prophet in his sufferings, or were known to be his particular friends. He that abused his power for the persecuting of God’s prophet, was left to himself further to abuse it for the crushing of his own subjects, whereby he weakened himself, and lost his interest. Most persecutors have been tyrants.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "16:1-14 Asa seeks the aid of the Syrians, His death. - A plain and faithful reproof was given to Asa by a prophet of the Lord, for making a league with Syria. God is displeased when he is distrusted, and when an arm of flesh is relied on, more than his power and goodness. It is foolish to lean on a broken reed, when we have the Rock of ages to rely upon. To convince Asa of his folly, the prophet shows that he, of all men, had no reason to distrust God, who had found him such a powerful Helper. The many experiences we have had of the goodness of God to us, aggravate our distrust of him. But see how deceitful our hearts are! we trust in God when we have nothing else to trust to, when need drives us to him; but when we have other things to stay on, we are apt to depend too much on them. Observe Asa's displeasure at this reproof. What is man, when God leaves him to himself! He that abused his power for persecuting God's prophet, was left to himself, to abuse it further for crushing his own subjects. Two years before he died, Asa was diseased in his feet. Making use of physicians was his duty; but trusting to them, and expecting that from them which was to be had from God only, were his sin and folly. In all conflicts and sufferings we need especially to look to our own hearts, that they may be perfect towards God, by faith, patience, and obedience.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
